default&#xa0;defaultAdvantages and disadvantagesdefault&#xa0;
defaultCECA believes that the introduction of Local Transport Bodies 
default(LTBs) 
defaultcould play a key role in improving 
defaultdecision-making on local 
defaulttransport expenditure
default. LTBs remove 
defaultthe need for a centralised bidding process and monetary
default bidding thresholds and ensure
default 
defaultdecisions are made locally
default rather than introducing centralised 
defaultand one-sized fits all 
defaultsolutions
default from Westminster
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, CECA remains concerned that the proposals to devol
defaultve funding for transport to 
defaultlocal bodies
default 
defaultmay lead to a lack of strategic decision-making in local communities. CECA supports the proposal for local communities to be able to make decisions in relat
defaultion to their 
defaultarea. However we remain concerned about a potential lack of collaborative working between LEPs
default and other local bodies
default to deliver significant projects across their geographical boundaries.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultAre there better models?default&#xa0;
defaultGiven that 
defaultLTBs are not yet
default in full operation
default, it is hard to tell whether 
defaultthey will be effective solutions
default. However, CECA notes that there 
defaultare already some 
defaultexamples of how local decision making on transport expenditure is proving to be a success. 
default&#xa0;
defaultLondon transport is perhaps the best example of effective local decision making. In London all transport 
defaultpolicy and funding 
defaultis decided by the Mayor’s Office and put into place by Transport for London (TfL). Transport policies developed by TfL have improved
default services, reduced journey times and reduced congestion within Greater London. 
defaultHowever, it is important to note that London is the only city in the UK to have developed such an integrated, locally focused and locally delivered transport system. 
default&#xa0;
defaultDesk based research has suggested that the model adopted in Barcelona is a good 
defaultinternational 
defaultexample of organisation and innovation. In this case governance takes the form of a joint management board and joint executive committee with equal membership bet
defaultween the Catalonian Government and local authorities. Notably the Barcelona model is funded by the state government, the Catalonian government and by local authorities. As a result of collaborative working, Barcelona has gained a reputation for transport i
defaultnnovatio
defaultn. Furthermore, there have been i
defaultmprovements in customer satisfaction and passenger growth.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultCECA believes that while the bodies referenced above will have excellent knowledge of their individual organisation
defaultal challenges, they may need assistance in working together effectively 
defaultas a
default delivery body. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWe believe that local bodies are best placed to decide what the transport priorities are in their area, although they should be supported in their decision-making
default process through the availability of 
defaultrobust
default evaluation models 
defaultthat have been developed by the Department of Transport. This will build confidence that 
defaultany decisions taken are evidence-based rather than politically motiovated. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhen it comes to the delivery of schemes 
defaultmany local authorities 
defaultface limitations on the resources available to them, with limited experience of the challeneges associated with the delivery of occasional lar
defaultg
defaulte projects
default, CECA proposes the creation of a trans
defaultport ‘Flying Squad’ to assist local bodies 
defaultin
default the development of
default such
default major infrastructure projects. Such a group could include, for example, representatives from industry and central Government working in partnership with local bodies to ensure that the m
defaultost effective and beneficial projects are developed. The flying squad could also provide expertise on procurement practice to minimise cost and delay.
default&#xa0;
defaultAn example of collaborative working can also be found in the Local Infrastructure Demonstrators Pilots p
defaultrogramme.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultBox 1: Local Infrastructure Demonstrators Pilots programmedefault&#xa0;
defaultThe Local Infrastructure Demonstrators Pilots programme is a private-led partnership (comprising CECA, the Royal Town Planning Institute, Department for Business, Innovation and Skills
default and local project co-ordinators). The partnership aims to progress stalled local infrastructure projects with potential to release economic growth by resolving barriers to progress.
default&#xa0;
defaultMultidisciplinary teams of experts (working on a pro-bono basis) nominat
defaulted by the partnership have been invited by local authorities to assist a small number of local projects in the first wave.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe partnership approach involves face-to-face interaction with local partners to uncover and understand barriers to progress. 
defaultTypical barriers include local co-ordination and capacity issues as much as, or rather than, access to finance.
