default&#xa0;
defaultCECA’s primary concern with regard to the devolution of transport decision-making to local bodies relates to how such organisations deal with opportunities to invest in infrastructure where doing so crossed boundaries. 
defaultEffective long-term planning with cro
defaultss-authority support and cooperation is essential to delivering projects to time and to budget. 
default&#xa0;
defaultA case in point can be seen in the Atlantic Gateway redevelopment in North West England which highlights the need for greater integration at local and regiona
defaultl level. The redevelopment project crosses three LEP areas and over a dozen local authorities. A small steering group has been established, but CECA feels that its focus is more on promoting the project rather than programme management, funding, co-ordinat
defaultion, joining up employment and training. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultIn order to further ensure delivery of cross-boundary projects, CECA calls on Government to intervene when it becomes apparent that local bodies are not working together effectively. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultThe effectiveness of collaborative working varies across the UK. To ensure that these variations do not continue after 2015, CECA calls on Government to ensure th
defaultat LEPs in partnership with local bodies give and demonstrate real consideration as to what will be best for their local community. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is essential that the right evidence based approach is adopte
defaultd for all
default local decision making. Transport solutions must 
defaultcome from solid, independent, research rather than tailoring evidence to
default develop a project
default. In this regard, CECA recommends that local communities continue to work closely with the Department for Transport 
default(DfT) 
defaultto develop an approved evidence collection a
defaultnd transport solution model. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCECA would not wish to see a scenario where local bodies attempt to ensure that every areas gets its “share” of funding if this stands in the way of delivering the most economical and socially beneficial projects. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe way that Government funds major local transport projects will radically change from 2015 when major transport scheme 
defaultfunding is devolved to LEPs as part of the Single Local Growth Fund.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe funding, taken from existing Whitehall funds will enable LEPs to bid for funding from a “single pot”. CECA believes that the funding, if used effectively, has the potential to rebala
defaultnce the economy through the development of ambitious local transport schemes and 
defaultwill enable LEPs and Local Transport Bodies to show what real added value they can bring. CECA anticipates that if the devolution of funding is successful, more will follow fo
defaultr further projects. 
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, we remain concerned that money allocated through the Growth 
defaultFund for transport projects could be diverted to other, non-transport projects. C
defaultECA 
defaultsuggests that once
default funding is
default allocated to a particular project, 
defaultit 
defaultremains ring
default-fenced specifically for that project. 
defaultWe hope that clear guidance will be provided to those in receipt of Growth Deal funding. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe provision of major project funding devolution and the Single Local Growth fund opens up the potential of improved visibility of future investment. 
default&#xa0;
defaultClear pipeline visibility is essential to ensure that cross boundary transport schemes are delivered ef
defaultfectively. Significant benefits and efficiencies will arise where greater forward visibility is available to the supply chain in terms of future investment. The key benefits associated with pipeline visibility are listed below, but CECA remains concerned t
defaulthat there is no pipeline visibility for local transport after 2015. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultFor these reasons we believe that a condition should be placed on those receiving Single Local Growth Fund  that they publish and maintain 
defaulta forward pipeline of the infrastructure investments that they anticipate supporting. In doing so they will ensure the best possible response from industry, securing efficient delivery and local job creation.
